docs/working/ASSUMPTIONS.md-49-| A-045 | 005H rejection-note creation keeps `LoanApplication.application_status` unchanged as `submitted` and stores only `RejectionNote.note_status = draft/sent`; it does not invent a generic intake rejection status. | `screen-spec.md` S14 says the application status is updated after rejection-note output, but the implemented/source-backed application status vocabulary currently has `draft`, `submitted`, `incomplete_returned`, and `reference_generated` for this intake stage, while data-model rejection statuses are tied to later credit-assessment/sanction concepts. | `docs/source/screen-spec.md` S14; `docs/source/data-model.md` §13.6 and loan-application status vocabulary; `docs/source/api-contracts.md` §21.3-§21.4; `docs/slices/005H-rejection-note-shell.md` | 005H-rejection-note-shell and future eligibility/appraisal/sanction rejection slices | Medium | Yes | 2026-07-10 | Future appraisal/rejection slices should define the source-backed stored rejected status and then decide whether rejection-note creation, approval, or send performs that transition. |
docs/working/ASSUMPTIONS.md-50-| A-046 | 006A returns `member_active_check = manual_evidence_required` when a member is active but no source-backed continuous produce/service history exists; it does not infer BR-004 through BR-007 from membership status alone. Existing verified `Member.active_member_status` facts can still produce `pass` or `relaxation`. | BR-004 through BR-007 require produce/service history or relaxation evidence, but current persistence has only member/profile summary fields and no source-backed history rows for continuous-year calculation. Inventing a supply-history calculation would create a business rule the source documents do not state. | `docs/source/functional-spec.md` BR-004 through BR-007; `docs/source/data-model.md` §14.1; `docs/working/digests/epic-006-eligibility-loan-limit-appraisal.md` | 006A-active-member-eligibility-service and future active-member/supply-history slices | Medium | Yes | 2026-07-10 | Add source-backed produce/service history models and replace this manual-evidence result when the active-member history slice is implemented. |
docs/working/ASSUMPTIONS.md-51-| A-047 | 006C treats exactly one active, effective, Board-referenced `LoanPolicyConfig` as the explicit operative loan-limit configuration. A configured percentage produces `valuation_per_share × percentage`; a configured per-share cap is the per-share ceiling; when both are present the lower per-share value applies. No applicable policy, multiple applicable policies, or neither positive share rule blocks calculation without success evidence. | The source requires percentage or per-share-cap configuration and says the API must expose the exact rule/version/source, but it does not spell out the interaction when both fields are populated. Treating the cap as a ceiling is the standard meaning of cap, reproduces the source §23.1 example (`10% of ₹2,000 = ₹200` with a ₹200 cap), and avoids choosing 30%, 10%, or ₹200 in code. | `docs/source/api-contracts.md` §23.1-§23.3; `docs/source/data-model.md` §14.2/§35.1; `docs/source/functional-spec.md` BR-019 through BR-025 and M01-FR-005/M01-FR-006 | 006C-loan-limit-configuration-and-calculator and future policy-governance slices | High | Yes | 2026-07-10 | The values remain versioned configuration, never hard-coded. If the client confirms mutually exclusive percentage/cap modes or another interaction, add an explicit rule-mode field and migrate calculation tests without rewriting historical assessment snapshots. |
docs/working/ASSUMPTIONS.md-52-| A-048 | 006D's policy-source snapshot columns allow null/blank only for database compatibility with assessment rows created before the migration. Every successful post-006D calculate/rerun stores policy config UUID, name, and Board reference; a legacy row is never enriched by reading mutable policy configuration during GET. | Existing 006C rows did not retain enough data to reconstruct policy source immutably. Backfilling from current policy rows could attach changed or ambiguous metadata and would violate historical integrity. | `docs/source/api-contracts.md` §23.3; `docs/source/data-model.md` §14.2, §35.1, §36.1; `docs/source/test-plan.md` MOD-LIMIT-009/MOD-LIMIT-010 | 006D-loan-limit-snapshot-storage | Medium | No | 2026-07-10 | If a deployed environment contains pre-006D assessments, an authorized successful rerun is the safe path to populate the new snapshot fields. GET returns null policy-source values for untouched legacy rows rather than consulting mutable config. |
docs/working/ASSUMPTIONS.md-53-| A-049 | Until the source defines how selected `LandHolding.area_acres`, `CropPlan.planned_area_acres`, and nullable profile `land_area_under_cultivation_acres` are reconciled for BR-020, 006C2 will block calculation when the applicable verified acreage facts disagree; it will not invent a min/max/priority formula. | Functional BR-020 requires acreage under cultivation, while the API/data model expose three related acreage facts without a precedence or reconciliation rule. Current 006C sums selected owned acreage and can overstate the land limit when cultivation evidence is lower. | `docs/source/functional-spec.md` BR-020/BR-022; `docs/source/api-contracts.md` §23.1-§23.3; `docs/source/data-model.md` §10.2, §11.7-§11.8, §14.2, §35.1; architecture review `2026-07-10_092630_architecture_review` | 006C2-cultivated-acreage-source-hardening and future policy confirmation | High | Yes | 2026-07-10 | Safe interim behavior is a structured validation blocker with no assessment/audit/workflow mutation. If the client confirms an authoritative source or formula, replace the equality guard, version the rule, and preserve existing snapshots. |
docs/working/ASSUMPTIONS.md-54-| A-050 | Application Detail composes API checklist rows with the existing card, badge, grid, tab, and empty-state patterns instead of reusing `DocumentChecklist`, because that prototype component imports `mockData` and synthesizes borrower/nominee/witness identifiers, documentation execution, security, and readiness facts. | 005I4 requires the real application detail to display API checklist rows directly and forbids synthetic lifecycle/readiness facts; reusing the existing mock-backed component would violate the slice and expose invented values. | `docs/slices/005I4-application-detail-backend-state-hardening.md`; `docs/working/FRONTEND_DESIGN_RULES.md`; `sfpcl-lms/src/components/loan/DocumentChecklist.tsx` | 005I4-application-detail-backend-state-hardening and future documentation UI wiring | Medium | No | 2026-07-10 | The composition reuses only approved prototype classes/components and introduces no new colours, typography, card, badge, table, or layout system. Replace it with the owning future API-backed documentation component when that workflow lands. |
docs/working/ASSUMPTIONS.md-55-| A-051 | `LoanAppraisalNote` stores UUID snapshots of the eligibility and loan-limit assessments used at creation, rather than foreign keys to their concrete Django models. | The slice requires appraisal to consume and preserve prerequisite IDs through projection-only module seams, while the source §14.4 table omits explicit prerequisite columns and 006D3 prohibits coupling appraisal to concrete assessment ownership. UUID snapshots preserve traceability and historical locality without allowing appraisal to navigate or mutate assessment rows. | `docs/source/data-model.md` §14.3-§14.4; `docs/source/codebase-design.md` §12.3; `docs/slices/006E-appraisal-note-create-edit-submit.md`; Epic 006 digest | 006E-appraisal-note-create-edit-submit and future appraisal review/reporting slices | Medium | Yes | 2026-07-10 | If source governance later requires formal FK constraints, add them behind the credit module while keeping projection-only callers and immutable historical response behavior. |
docs/working/ASSUMPTIONS.md-56-| A-052 | Supersedes A-051's claim that assessment UUIDs alone preserve historical locality: explicit successful assessment reruns retain the UUID while replacing current facts, so 006E2 will keep the IDs only as provenance and persist immutable canonical projection copies on the appraisal. | Architecture review proved a same-UUID rerun can replace cultivated acreage, limits, policy, eligibility, and exception facts after appraisal creation. API design §3 requires decision snapshots; no FK to a mutable current assessment can provide that evidence. | `docs/adr/ADR-0003-freeze-appraisal-prerequisite-projections.md`; `docs/source/api-contracts.md` §3/§23-§24; architecture review `2026-07-10_173305_architecture_review` | 006E2-appraisal-source-contract-and-snapshot-hardening and later review/sanction/reporting slices | High | Yes | 2026-07-10 | Implement the additive immutable snapshots and safe legacy provenance rules before 006F. Do not alter the already reviewed explicit assessment-rerun contract. |
docs/working/ASSUMPTIONS.md-57-| A-053 | M04-FR-001/M04-FR-002 appraisal task creation/role assignment remain intentionally deferred to the owner-planned generic task engine in 012EA; `prepared_by_user` is an action fact, not a substitute for assignment. | The current schema has no persisted workflow task/assignment resource, and 005I5 explicitly prohibits relabelling receiver/creator as assignment. 012EA already owns persisted task generation after workflow states exist. | `docs/source/functional-spec.md` M04-FR-001/M04-FR-002; `docs/slices/012EA-workflow-task-engine-and-task-inbox-apis.md`; architecture review `2026-07-10_173305_architecture_review` | 012EA-workflow-task-engine-and-task-inbox-apis | High | Yes | 2026-07-10 | Epic 006 must not claim these IDs complete before 012EA creates one idempotent Deputy Manager – Finance appraisal task after application-number generation and backfills existing applications. |
docs/working/ASSUMPTIONS.md-58-| A-054 | Until source governance selects between application receipt and completeness confirmation for M04-FR-003, the current appraisal TAT anchor remains `LoanApplication.created_at`, the timestamp used by 006E as the available application-receipt proxy. | Functional M04-FR-003 says receipt / completeness confirmation, data-model §14.4 says application receipt + 2 days, and the current model has no completeness-confirmed timestamp. Choosing a different inferred timestamp would invent a rule. | `docs/source/functional-spec.md` M04-FR-003; `docs/source/data-model.md` §14.4; `docs/slices/006E-appraisal-note-create-edit-submit.md`; architecture review `2026-07-10_173305_architecture_review` | 006E2 and future workflow-task/SLA governance | High | Yes | 2026-07-10 | Keep the anchor explicit in API/contracts and task due-date generation. If the owner confirms completeness confirmation, add a persisted confirmation timestamp and version the SLA rule without rewriting historical due dates. |
docs/working/ASSUMPTIONS.md:59:| A-055 | Authoritative loan-limit concurrency tests run only through `sfpcl_credit.config.postgres_test_settings`; the default SQLite suite explicitly skips them because SQLite does not implement `SELECT ... FOR UPDATE`. PostgreSQL connection values are environment supplied, with conventional local defaults. | Codebase-design §26.3 requires concurrency tests for financial modules, while the existing local settings are SQLite-only and the source requires PostgreSQL for production. Treating SQLite success as row-lock evidence would be false assurance. | `docs/source/codebase-design.md` §22.3/§26.3; `docs/source/data-model.md` §34; `docs/slices/006D2C-loan-limit-concurrency-and-boundary-regression.md`; `docs/working/DEPENDENCY_POLICY.md` | 006D2C and every future change to loan-limit locking | High | Yes | 2026-07-10 | Independent validation must install pinned `psycopg[binary]`, provision PostgreSQL, and run `manage.py test sfpcl_credit.tests.test_credit_modules.LoanLimitConcurrencyTests --settings=sfpcl_credit.config.postgres_test_settings -v 2`; a SQLite skip is never acceptance evidence. |
docs/working/ASSUMPTIONS.md-60-| A-056 | Ambiguous legacy appraisal repair uses `POST /api/v1/appraisal-notes/{id}/revalidate-prerequisites/` with an empty body, appraisal-update plus risk-management permission, object scope, and draft-only state. | ADR-0003 and 006E2 require explicit authorised revalidation but the source API document does not name its path/body. A dedicated action endpoint matches API §3, avoids overloading PATCH, and changes only frozen prerequisite facts. | `docs/source/api-contracts.md` §3/§24; `docs/adr/ADR-0003-freeze-appraisal-prerequisite-projections.md`; `docs/slices/006E2-appraisal-source-contract-and-snapshot-hardening.md` | 006E2 and later appraisal review/sanction slices | High | Yes | 2026-07-10 | If governance names a different repair action, version/alias the route while retaining draft-only authorisation, immutable caller-authored facts, and metadata-only evidence. |
docs/working/ASSUMPTIONS.md-61-| A-057 | A rejected Credit Manager review extends the §24.4 request with top-level `rejection_reason_category`, `detailed_reason`, `reapply_allowed_flag`, and `communication_mode`; `rejection_stage` is fixed by the workflow to `credit_assessment`. These extra fields are required only for `decision = rejected`, while `reviewed` and `returned` continue to accept exactly `decision` and `review_comments`. | M04-FR-011 requires the review action to generate the existing rejection note, but §24.4 names only decision/comments while §21.3 and data-model §13.6 require category, detailed reason, reapply flag, and communication mode. Requiring the source fields avoids inventing defaults; fixing the stage is an invariant of the appraisal workflow rather than caller choice. | `docs/source/functional-spec.md` M04-FR-011; `docs/source/api-contracts.md` §21.3/§24.4; `docs/source/data-model.md` §13.6; `docs/slices/006F2-credit-manager-appraisal-rejection.md` | 006F2 and later rejection/sanction slices | High | Yes | 2026-07-10 | If source governance defines a nested request or different review fields, version the adapter while retaining the public appraisal/rejection-note module seams and existing stored note contract. |
docs/working/ASSUMPTIONS.md-62-| A-058 | Appraisal responses expose chronological `review_history[]`; new rows use `history_provenance = native`, while the single reconstructable migration backfill uses `legacy_latest_only`. Reversing migration 0005 removes the derived history table but preserves conservative `legacy_unverified` provenance rather than recreating a known false verification. | ADR-0004 requires append-only appraisal-owned review decisions and an explicitly labelled latest-only legacy backfill, but the source API/schema does not name the response field, provenance enum values, or unsafe reverse-label behavior. These explicit names keep latest projections backward compatible and make incomplete legacy evidence visible. | `docs/adr/ADR-0003-freeze-appraisal-prerequisite-projections.md`; `docs/adr/ADR-0004-append-only-appraisal-review-decisions.md`; `docs/source/api-contracts.md` §3/§24.4; `docs/source/data-model.md` §14.4/§34 | 006E3 and later appraisal/sanction/reporting slices | High | Yes | 2026-07-10 | If governance standardises different history/provenance names, version the response adapter without rewriting stored decisions or upgrading unproven prerequisite provenance. |
